body:
I feel as if some people on this thread are misusing ABI vs API breaking? Does everyone understand what an ABI-but-not-API breaking change is?

Like, this change breaks ABI but _not_ API:

``` c
// In v1.0.0
struct Foo {
   int bar;
   char baz[32];
};

// In v1.0.1
struct Foo {
   char baz[32];
   int bar;
};

// In v1.0.0 bar is located at +0 from the beginning of the struct, in v1.0.1 this is at +0x20
// Compiling this code from source works in both v1.0.0 and v1.0.1, it is not an API break
// but it _is_ an ABI break.
myFoo->bar = 5;
```

@juliangruber It does not bring any clarity to me.
The [code](https://github.com/nodejs/nan/blob/master/nan.h#L526-533) in question hardly does anything.

``` c++
inline v8::Local<v8::Primitive> Null() {
  return v8::Null(v8::Isolate::GetCurrent());
}
```

So the most likely source of error is indeed an ABI incompatibility.

`v8::Null` is defined [here](https://github.com/v8/v8/blob/5.1.281/include/v8.h#L8509-8515)

``` c++
Local<Primitive> Null(Isolate* isolate) {
  typedef internal::Object* S;
  typedef internal::Internals I;
  I::CheckInitialized(isolate);
  S* slot = I::GetRoot(isolate, I::kNullValueRootIndex);
  return Local<Primitive>(reinterpret_cast<Primitive*>(slot));
}
```

`v8::True` is defined [here](https://github.com/v8/v8/blob/5.1.281/include/v8.h#L8518-8524)

``` c++
Local<Boolean> True(Isolate* isolate) {
  typedef internal::Object* S;
  typedef internal::Internals I;
  I::CheckInitialized(isolate);
  S* slot = I::GetRoot(isolate, I::kTrueValueRootIndex);
  return Local<Boolean>(reinterpret_cast<Boolean*>(slot));
}
```

`v8::Boolean` is a `v8::Primitive`, so the only significant difference between the two functions is `I::kNullValueRootIndex` vs `I::kTrueValueRootIndex`.

In [V8 5.0.71](https://github.com/v8/v8/blob/5.0.71/include/v8.h#L7159-7160), we have

``` c++
  static const int kNullValueRootIndex = 7;
  static const int kTrueValueRootIndex = 8;
```

In [V8 5.1.281](https://github.com/v8/v8/blob/5.1.281/include/v8.h#L7337-7338), we have

``` c++
  static const int kNullValueRootIndex = 6;
  static const int kTrueValueRootIndex = 7;
```

So, the ABI incompatiblity is obvious: the precompiled addon, correctly using the ABI for V8 5.0.71 calls `v8::Null`, which returns the field at index 7. When using the wrong V8 version, like Electron does, this ends up returning `true` instead of `null`, since the ABI changed and `true` is now located at index 7.

we have been fighting this as well.

> will probably be a super painful proposition in the Chromium codebase

@paulcbetts, I don't understand ^^ remark.  can you clarify?

@rvagg If the changes are solely to massage ABI compatibility (or are fairly minor), we can probably cover that, since we build everything from source anyways, though @zcbenz is the expert.

The most foolproof seems as if the node ABI/API and the V8 ABI/API would be expressed in separate numbers (i.e. declare a certain `NODE_MODULE_VERSION` to be The Last One and from then on it's `V8_MODULE_VERSION` and `NODEAPI_MODULE_VERSION`). This would make intent easier to express in places like nan. 

This is a pretty radical change though, and I don't know that Electron/nw.js's problems merit making life more complicated for the larger node.js world (though if we did it right we could hide a lot of this behind nan)

